04765nam a22007095i 9789815011579DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222022si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898150115797 a10.1355/97898150115792doi  a(DE-B1597)634017  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 4aDS501b.I59T 2022 7aSOC0480002bisacsh04a950223/eng/202207251 aMohd, Faizal Musa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMuslim Sectarianism versus the De-escalation of Sectarianism in Malaysia /cFaizal Musa Mohd. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (64 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tMuslim Sectarianism versus the De-escalation of Sectarianism in Malaysia. EXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tMuslim Sectarianism versus the De-escalation of Sectarianism in Malaysia -- tAPPENDIX Summary of Treatment of Shia Muslims in Malaysia on Freedom of Religion, Freedom of Expression, and Cultural Rights, 26 August 1996 – 26 September 2014 -- tREFERENCES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMalaysia was initially lauded for its ability to combat the first few waves of COVID-19 but infection spikes since the Sabah state elections in September 2020 and subsequent exponential increases in both infections and deaths in 2021 left the nation reeling. Nationwide vaccination is seen as the only way out of the pandemic. Malaysia’s COVID-19 communication strategy was hampered by political machinations and myriad changes in government. The need to shore up favour among the electorate resulted in inconsistent messaging and regular U-turns whenever there was public outrage at arbitrary restrictions. This resulted in confusion on the ground, preventing successful COVID-19 management and containment. Under the current regime, claims to more accessible data have been disputed and doubts have surfaced over data transparency and accuracy. There is an urgent need to ensure convincingly reliable information, as well as to use more engaging messaging on more suitable media. A holistic and effective COVID-19 communication strategy should adopt principles from several communication approaches, resulting in messages that are clear, simple and accessible as well as consistent and credible. Audiences should be segmented so that messages can be better tailored to their needs, with adequate information on the necessary steps to prevent infection and spread. Fake news, misinformation, and disinformation should be constantly tackled and debunked. The Gerai OA and OA Lindungi Komuniti Facebook pages are outstanding examples of grassroots information dissemination channels that effectively provide fact-checked, coherent and accessible information to local communities in languages and on media best-suited to their audiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aShīʻahxRelationszMalaysiaxSunnites. 0aSunnitesxRelationszMalaysiaxShīʻah. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh1 aFaizal Musa, Mohd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2z978311076700108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076711740uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981501157940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789815011579423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789815011579/original  a978-3-11-076700-1  DG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2b2022  a978-3-11-076711-7  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  